Amway (short for "American Way") is an American company specializing in the use of multi-level marketing to sell health, beauty, and home care products.[3][4][5] It was founded in 1959 by Jay Van Andel and Richard DeVos.[citation needed]
Based in Ada, Michigan, Amway and its sister companies under Alticor reported sales of $9.5 billion in 2015.[6] It conducts business through a number of affiliated companies in more than a hundred countries and territories. Based on revenue, Amway was ranked No. 29 among the largest privately-held companies in the United States by Forbes in 2015, and No. 1 among multi-level marketing companies by Direct Selling News in 2016.[7][8][9]
Amway has been investigated in various countries, by institutions such as the Federal Trade Commission (FTC), for alleged pyramid scheme practices.[10][11][12][13][14] The FTC investigations took place from 1970–79, and afterward, the FTC began using Amway as the model for all other multi-level marketing companies.[clarification needed][citation needed]
Studies of independent consumer watchdog agencies have shown that between 990 and 999 of 1000 participants in MLMs that use Amway-type pay plans in fact lose money.[15][16][citation needed]
The Federal Trade Commission requires Amway to label its products with the message that 54% of Amway recruits make nothing and the rest earn on average $65 a month.[17][citation needed]



